In this, both plaintiff and defendant were, until decision of the suit, regarded by the law as equally entitled to the dominium. It was necessary, how- ever, that one of them should be magisterially instated in the pos- session of the disputed property pending litigation, and we learn from Gaius (iv. 16) how such interim possession was awarded. Having been magisterially awarded, it must also be magisterially protected, and this was done by an interdict3 a remedy which oeme subsequently to be used for the protection of all Possession, independently of a pending suit.
